# Cross-Repo Fix: Replace CI Polling with Event-Driven CI-Ready Signal

## Problem

When `craft publish` runs, it polls the GitHub commit status/check runs API every 30 seconds for up to 60 minutes (`BaseStatusProvider.waitForTheBuildToSucceed()` in `src/status_providers/base.ts:82-146`). This eats into the 1-hour GitHub App token lifetime and is the root cause of the expired-token merge failure we just fixed.

## Solution Overview

Replace the polling loop with a **repository_dispatch** signal from the target repo's CI. The publish repo uses labels as a state machine:

| Label        | Added by                                  | Meaning                                    |
| ------------ | ----------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| `ci-pending` | `action.yml` (at issue creation)          | CI signal expected but not yet received    |
| `ci-ready`   | new `ci-ready.yml` workflow (on dispatch) | CI passed, safe to publish without polling |
| `accepted`   | Human or `auto-approve.yml`               | Approved for publishing                    |

Publishing only starts when both `accepted` AND `ci-ready` are present (for opted-in repos). Old repos work exactly as before.

